TikTok hides unpleasant videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
Imagine China/Reuters
The Chinese social network TikTok is subject to censorship of videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibetan independence, or the forbidden religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
The documents found at the publications say that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance) is promoting China’s foreign policy goals overseas through the app.
The main part of China’s policy violations is under the “hate spark”.
In each case, TikTok places inappropriate publications in a context that is appropriate under general rules so that the actions of the social network do not appear to be censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China’s socialist system falls under a general ban on “criticism or attacks on any country’s policies and social rules, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on the mention of incidents on the Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the “history of China or other countries.”
The document also includes a list of the banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or state figures", including North Korean leaders Kim Chen Ira, Kim Ir Sen and Kim Chen Yin, Indian politician President Preyano, President Obama, President Obama, President Obama, President Donald Trump, President Donald Trump and President Obama.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, as stated in the document.
Posts from the first category are removed by social network administrators and can result in the user being blocked.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applicable: “We are now using a localized approach to moderation, and we are also attracting independent local experts.”
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says co-founder of the “Producer Center” Rustem Bogdanov.
"Producer Center" is one of the Russian media companies, which officially cooperates with TikTok.
All the advertising materials of the bloggers "Producer Center" agrees with the representatives of the social network, but the user material can be posted without consent, Bogdanov transmits.
Asked whether TikTok could speak about politics or Putin, Bogdanov answered affirmatively and said he had seen such publications.
Bogdanov agrees with the founder of the agency Our Diddigital Roman Zaripov: “The basic rules for users TikTok lists in the user agreement: it is not possible to expose shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on.”
But under these rules you can summarize any content that does not like moderators, Zarypov notes.
Zaripova is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
According to the User Agreement, only persons over the age of 13 may use TikTok.
Social network administrators check their age using artificial intelligence: the neuronet analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neuronet decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
